# self-monitoring-pack ontology -- vocabulary for treating one Claude Code
# CONVERSATIONAL TURN (not a tool event; see packs/dogfood-lifecycle-pack for
# that) as PROV-O provenance, so that a real `kh:` Knowledge Hook
# (hook.ttl, this pack) can pattern-match over a session's turn history and
# derive an escalation obligation -- dogfooding the EXACT mechanism already
# proven this session for the Solvane Global bribery case's obligation
# derivation (crates/multifractal-workflow/fixtures/bribery-case/hook.ttl +
# crates/multifractal-workflow/tests/bribery_case_fixture.rs), applied here
# to Claude Code's own answer-format pattern instead of a compliance case.
#
# SIBLING PACK, SAME DISCIPLINE as packs/dogfood-lifecycle-pack/ontology.ttl:
# public-ontology-first, PROV-O for the activity shape, closed SKOS schemes
# for enumerations, every minted term disclosed with the public ontologies
# checked and why they do not fit.
#
# ============================================================================
# CLASSIFICATION-IS-INPUT FENCE (read this before using this pack for
# anything) -- the single most important scope boundary in this pack, and the
# discipline this whole exercise exists to demonstrate:
#
#   The turn-kind classification (is this turn a GroundingQuestion? was the
#   turn that followed it a SurveyResponse or a RunResponse?) is an INPUT
#   FACT this vocabulary's properties CARRY -- smon:turnKind is asserted BY
#   SOMETHING ELSE (a human, an upstream classifier, a disclosed manual
#   annotation pass) before hook.ttl's Knowledge Hook ever runs. Datalog/
#   SPARQL-CONSTRUCT pattern-matches over ALREADY-CLASSIFIED facts; it does
#   not classify raw natural-language turn text itself. Building an NLP
#   classifier that reads free-text Claude Code output and outputs
#   smon:turnKind values is a SEPARATE, OUT-OF-SCOPE problem this pack does
#   not attempt, does not stub, and does not claim to solve. Every fixture in
#   fixtures/ hand-asserts smon:turnKind directly (exactly as hook.ttl's own
#   precedent, the bribery case's case.ttl, hand-asserts
#   sc:allegesImproperPayment rather than deriving "improper" from an email
#   body) -- the CONSTRUCT query in hook.ttl only ever reads smon:turnKind,
#   dcterms:subject, and smon:immediatelyFollows; it never reads or reasons
#   over a turn's actual text content (no turn-content literal is even
#   modeled in this vocabulary).
# ============================================================================
#
# Public vocabularies used (NOT redefined here -- used by IRI):
#   prov:    a conversational TURN is a prov:Activity (smon:Turn subclass,
#            disclosed below), matching packs/dogfood-lifecycle-pack's own
#            dfl:Session/dfl:ToolEvent-as-prov:Activity pattern and
#            crates/multifractal-workflow/fixtures/bribery-case/case.ttl's
#            sc:ComplianceCase-as-prov:Activity pattern.
#   dcterms: dcterms:isPartOf   turn -> the session it belongs to (the
#            "session reference"; PROV core has no sub-activity predicate,
#            so, exactly as packs/dogfood-lifecycle-pack/ontology.ttl's
#            header already argues for dfl:ToolEvent, the public DCMI
#            part/whole relation carries it). THE RANGE OF THIS PROPERTY, ON
#            A smon:Turn, IS dfl:Session -- this pack does NOT re-mint its
#            own session class; it reuses packs/dogfood-lifecycle-pack's
#            dfl:Session directly (same Claude Code session concept, same
#            IRI-reuse discipline this whole task's doctrine requires:
#            "instance data reuses IRIs across files, never re-mints" --
#            applied here one level up, at the VOCABULARY layer, by pointing
#            the range at the already-disclosed dfl:Session class rather
#            than inventing a parallel smon:Session).
#            dcterms:subject   THIS IS THE TASK BRIEF'S "grounding_topic":
#            "the topic of the resource" is exactly "which system/capability
#            this turn is asking about" -- checked and used DIRECTLY, no
#            minting needed. dcterms:subject's own definition permits either
#            a free-text keyword/phrase or a controlled-vocabulary IRI term
#            as its value, matching the task brief's "free-text or IRI tag"
#            requirement without any bridge term.
#   skos:    skos:ConceptScheme + skos:Concept + skos:notation + skos:inScheme
#            model the closed turn-kind vocabulary exactly as
#            packs/dogfood-lifecycle-pack/ontology.ttl's dfl:OutcomeScheme
#            models tool-event outcomes (closed SKOS concepts, not a minted
#            class hierarchy).
#
# DISCLOSED MINTED TERMS (smon:, capability-justified -- no public equivalent):
#   smon:Turn  rdfs:subClassOf prov:Activity. PROV has no subtype for "one
#     conversational turn within a session, requiring a turn-kind
#     classification and a topic tag"; checked prov: (no such subtype) and
#     schema.org Action/Message/CommunicateAction (models a completed
#     communicative act generically, but pulls in an unrelated commercial
#     vocabulary and has no closed-vocabulary "kind" slot the way SHACL needs
#     a precise sh:targetClass to constrain). Mirrors dfl:ToolEvent's and
#     sc:ComplianceCase's identical minted-subclass-of-prov:Activity
#     rationale (both already disclosed in their own files).
#   smon:sequenceIndex  monotonic per-session ordinal (xsd:integer),
#     mirroring dfl:sequenceIndex's IDENTICAL disclosed rationale in
#     packs/dogfood-lifecycle-pack/ontology.ttl (OLO's olo:index requires a
#     fully materialized olo:OrderedList; a capture hook emitting an
#     incrementing counter is far lighter). Not reused directly as the SAME
#     property because dfl:sequenceIndex's rdfs:domain is dfl:ToolEvent, a
#     different activity subtype than smon:Turn; minting the domain-scoped
#     analogue keeps each pack's SHACL shape precise without weakening
#     dfl:ToolEventShape's own domain assumption.
#   smon:immediatelyFollows  Turn -> Turn, "the subject turn is the very
#     next turn, in session order, after the object turn." Checked OLO
#     (olo:index gives ordinal POSITION within a materialized ordered list,
#     not a direct pairwise adjacency edge a capture hook can assert cheaply
#     per new turn) and rejected for the same reason dfl:sequenceIndex
#     rejects it. This property exists so hook.ttl's CONSTRUCT query can
#     express "the turn immediately following turn X" as a plain graph-
#     pattern join (?resp smon:immediatelyFollows ?x) instead of SPARQL
#     arithmetic on sequenceIndex (?ir = ?i1 + 1) -- confirmed by reading
#     crates/praxis-graphlaw/src/sparql/plan.rs::extract_expression this
#     session: `Expression::Add`/`Subtract` are NOT matched by that function
#     (they fall through to the `_ => PlanExpression::Done` catch-all), so
#     arithmetic FILTER expressions are NOT a proven capability of this
#     engine. Using a direct adjacency edge instead of `+1` arithmetic keeps
#     hook.ttl within confirmed-supported SPARQL (BGP joins + Greater/
#     NotEqual comparisons, both exercised live by
#     crates/praxis-graphlaw/tests/soc2_hook_actuation.rs and
#     crates/multifractal-workflow/fixtures/bribery-case/hook.ttl already).
#   smon:turnKind + smon:TurnKind  a turn's classification, drawn from the
#     CLOSED 5-concept vocabulary below (smon:TurnKindScheme). No public
#     ontology enumerates conversational-turn-answer-format classifications;
#     mirrors dfl:outcome + dfl:Outcome's IDENTICAL closed-scheme pattern.
#     dcterms:type was checked and rejected for the same reason
#     packs/dogfood-lifecycle-pack/ontology.ttl's header already rejects it
#     for dfl:outcome: it names a resource's genre, not an observed
#     classification of a specific process step.
#   smon:EscalationObligation  the derived-fact node hook.ttl's CONSTRUCT
#     query produces. No public ontology models "a pattern-match finding
#     linking two triggering activities with role-distinguishing
#     predicates" -- PROV's prov:wasDerivedFrom/prov:wasInformedBy were
#     checked and rejected: prov:wasDerivedFrom's domain and range are both
#     prov:Entity, but smon:Turn is deliberately modeled as a prov:Activity
#     (an occurrence with duration and a kind classification, not a static
#     entity), so asserting wasDerivedFrom FROM a Turn is a type mismatch,
#     not merely an unfashionable choice; prov:wasInformedBy relates two
#     Activities directly (no intervening derived-fact node), which cannot
#     carry this pack's smon:reason literal or distinguish "prior" from
#     "repeat" turn roles the way this pack's two role-scoped properties do.
#     A plain rdfs:Class (not subclassed under prov: at all), mirroring
#     crates/multifractal-workflow/fixtures/bribery-case/hook.ttl's
#     sc:Obligation -- a category/fact-marker node, not a temporally-extended
#     PROV activity or entity in its own right.
#   smon:hasPriorGroundingQuestion  EscalationObligation -> the FIRST
#     GroundingQuestion turn (the one whose immediately-following response
#     was a SurveyResponse). No public equivalent -- see smon:EscalationObligation
#     disclosure above.
#   smon:hasGroundingQuestion  EscalationObligation -> the REPEAT
#     GroundingQuestion turn (the later, same-topic turn that reveals the
#     system was asked about again). No public equivalent -- see above.
#   smon:reason  EscalationObligation -> an xsd:string literal explaining
#     the derivation. Mirrors kh:reason's already-established, repo-wide
#     "a literal naming why a governed fact was produced" pattern
#     (crates/praxis-graphlaw/src/hooks/mod.rs's kh:reason on refusing
#     hooks), scoped to this pack's derived-fact node rather than a hook
#     definition (different domain, same rationale). dcterms:description was
#     checked and rejected: it is a generic "account of the resource," not
#     specifically the causal rationale a pattern-derivation exists to name.
#
# ============================================================================
# L5-PUSH ADDITIONS (this pass) -- disclosed exactly like every other minted
# term above, not silently introduced:
#
#   smon:severity + smon:Severity  a CLOSED 3-concept severity scheme (Low /
#     Medium / High) attached to smon:EscalationObligation, so a downstream
#     planner has a real, usable prioritization signal instead of a bare
#     unparameterized obligation node (Matrix 2's Derivation-power L3 bar:
#     "Derives obligations with parameters ... usable by a downstream
#     planner"). NOT a hardcoded constant: hook.ttl's companion
#     `smon:prioritize_escalation_obligation` hook (below) computes it from a
#     real COUNT(?otherQ) aggregate over how many OTHER same-topic
#     GroundingQuestion turns exist in the session (confirmed live, this
#     pass, against crates/praxis-graphlaw/src/sparql/plan.rs: `Aggregate`/
#     `PlanAggregationFunction::Count` IS implemented, unlike
#     Expression::Add/Subtract, which is why deadline below stays
#     categorical rather than arithmetic on timestamps). No public ontology
#     term names "how urgent a derived governance finding is" as a closed,
#     hook-computed scheme; schema.org's `priority` is a free string with no
#     defined vocabulary and no domain tie to a PROV-shaped finding node.
#   smon:deadlineHint + smon:DeadlineHint  a CLOSED 2-concept categorical
#     scheme (ActNow / NextSession) bound 1:1 to severity (High -> ActNow,
#     Low/Medium -> NextSession) by the SAME hook, never by arithmetic on
#     smon:sequenceIndex or a timestamp (this engine does not implement
#     Expression::Add -- see smon:immediatelyFollows's disclosure above,
#     unchanged and still true this pass). Deliberately NOT an xsd:dateTime:
#     asserting a fabricated absolute deadline the hook cannot actually
#     compute would be exactly the "fake it" failure this pass is required
#     to avoid.
#   smon:status + smon:ObligationStatus  a CLOSED 3-concept scheme (Open /
#     Discharged / Refused) on smon:EscalationObligation. The derivation
#     hook always asserts smon:status smon:Open (an obligation is born open);
#     nothing in this pack's hooks ever transitions it -- discharge/refusal
#     is recorded by a SEPARATE, later fact-assertion (exactly mirroring how
#     smon:turnKind itself is always an input fact, never hook-computed; see
#     the CLASSIFICATION-IS-INPUT FENCE above -- the SAME discipline applied
#     to lifecycle state). `queries/open_obligations.rq` (shipped this pass)
#     is the real, checked-in query surface over this property.
#   smon:dischargedAt + smon:refusalReason  xsd:dateTime / xsd:string on
#     EscalationObligation, present only once smon:status moves off Open;
#     required together with the corresponding status value by
#     shapes.ttl's new sh:or branch (below).
#   smon:UngovernedTransition  a SEPARATE derived-fact class (companion hook
#     `smon:flag_ungoverned_transition`, hook.ttl) marking a GroundingQuestion
#     turn whose immediately-following response is smon:Other -- i.e. NEITHER
#     a SurveyResponse (the one pattern this pack governs) NOR a RunResponse/
#     BlockerResponse (the two "handled correctly" kinds already proven never
#     to fire the escalation, per README's adversarial check 1). This is the
#     real, positive "any transition falling outside every governed pattern
#     is itself detectable and flagged" mechanism Matrix 2's Governance-
#     coverage L5 bar names -- scoped honestly to the ONE process this pack
#     actually models (the grounding-question/response pattern), not the
#     whole of Claude Code's behavior (see "still not L5" in this pass's
#     final scoring for why one governed happy-path plus this one catch-all
#     is not yet "the whole process").
# ============================================================================
#
# CLASSIFICATION-IS-INPUT FENCE: see the block above this header's public-
# vocabulary list. Repeated here at the end because it is the load-bearing
# constraint of this entire pack.

@prefix smon:    <http://seanchatmangpt.github.io/packs/self-monitoring#> .
@prefix dfl:     <http://seanchatmangpt.github.io/packs/dogfood-lifecycle#> .
@prefix prov:    <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov#> .
@prefix dcterms: <http://purl.org/dc/terms/> .
@prefix skos:    <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#> .
@prefix rdf:     <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#> .
@prefix rdfs:    <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix xsd:     <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .

# ── Classes (minted subclass of prov:Activity -- disclosed above) ─────────

smon:Turn
    a               rdfs:Class ;
    rdfs:subClassOf prov:Activity ;
    rdfs:label      "Turn" ;
    rdfs:comment    "One conversational turn (a single Claude Code reply) within a session, as a prov:Activity. Required attributes enforced by shapes.ttl: dcterms:isPartOf (session ref, sh:class dfl:Session), dcterms:subject (the grounding topic), smon:sequenceIndex, smon:turnKind (closed vocabulary). smon:immediatelyFollows is optional (asserted when the capture mechanism records direct adjacency). turnKind is an INPUT to this pack, never derived from turn text -- see this file's header CLASSIFICATION-IS-INPUT FENCE." .

smon:TurnKind
    a            rdfs:Class ;
    rdfs:label   "TurnKind" ;
    rdfs:comment "The closed class of conversational-turn classifications. Exactly five individuals exist (smon:GroundingQuestion, smon:SurveyResponse, smon:RunResponse, smon:BlockerResponse, smon:Other); do not add more without updating shapes.ttl's sh:in list in the same edit. Mirrors dfl:Outcome's closed-scheme pattern (packs/dogfood-lifecycle-pack/ontology.ttl)." .

smon:EscalationObligation
    a            rdfs:Class ;
    rdfs:label   "EscalationObligation" ;
    rdfs:comment "A derived fact: a repeated GroundingQuestion on the same topic, where the FIRST GroundingQuestion's immediately-following response was a SurveyResponse (not a RunResponse/BlockerResponse), warrants escalating to an actual build/run rather than another survey. Produced ONLY by hook.ttl's kh:Hook CONSTRUCT query -- never hand-asserted in fixture data. See this file's header for why this is a plain rdfs:Class, not subclassed under prov:." .

# ── Minted properties (disclosed above) ───────────────────────────────────

smon:sequenceIndex
    a            rdf:Property ;
    rdfs:label   "sequenceIndex" ;
    rdfs:domain  smon:Turn ;
    rdfs:range   xsd:integer ;
    rdfs:comment "Monotonic per-session ordinal of this turn (0-based or 1-based; strictly increasing within one session). Mirrors dfl:sequenceIndex's identical disclosed rationale, domain-scoped to smon:Turn instead of dfl:ToolEvent." .

smon:immediatelyFollows
    a            rdf:Property ;
    rdfs:label   "immediatelyFollows" ;
    rdfs:domain  smon:Turn ;
    rdfs:range   smon:Turn ;
    rdfs:comment "The subject turn is the very next turn, in session order, after the object turn. Exists so hook.ttl's CONSTRUCT query can express turn-adjacency as a plain graph-pattern join instead of SPARQL arithmetic on smon:sequenceIndex -- see this file's header for the confirmed engine-capability finding (Expression::Add is not implemented in crates/praxis-graphlaw/src/sparql/plan.rs::extract_expression) that this property exists to work around." .

smon:turnKind
    a            rdf:Property ;
    rdfs:label   "turnKind" ;
    rdfs:domain  smon:Turn ;
    rdfs:range   smon:TurnKind ;
    rdfs:comment "Links a turn to its classification individual (smon:GroundingQuestion / smon:SurveyResponse / smon:RunResponse / smon:BlockerResponse / smon:Other). Mirrors dfl:outcome. ALWAYS AN INPUT FACT, never computed by any hook in this pack -- see this file's header CLASSIFICATION-IS-INPUT FENCE." .

smon:hasPriorGroundingQuestion
    a            rdf:Property ;
    rdfs:label   "hasPriorGroundingQuestion" ;
    rdfs:domain  smon:EscalationObligation ;
    rdfs:range   smon:Turn ;
    rdfs:comment "Links a derived EscalationObligation to the FIRST (earlier) GroundingQuestion turn in the pair -- the one whose immediately-following response was a SurveyResponse. No public equivalent; see this file's header." .

smon:hasGroundingQuestion
    a            rdf:Property ;
    rdfs:label   "hasGroundingQuestion" ;
    rdfs:domain  smon:EscalationObligation ;
    rdfs:range   smon:Turn ;
    rdfs:comment "Links a derived EscalationObligation to the REPEAT (later) GroundingQuestion turn on the same grounding topic -- the turn whose existence, combined with the prior turn's survey-only response, triggers the escalation. No public equivalent; see this file's header." .

smon:reason
    a            rdf:Property ;
    rdfs:label   "reason" ;
    rdfs:domain  smon:EscalationObligation ;
    rdfs:range   xsd:string ;
    rdfs:comment "Free-text explanation of why the escalation was derived. Mirrors kh:reason's repo-wide pattern for a governed-fact rationale literal, scoped to this pack's derived-fact node. No public equivalent; see this file's header." .

# ── Closed turn-kind vocabulary (SKOS; INPUT classification only) ────────

smon:TurnKindScheme
    a            skos:ConceptScheme ;
    rdfs:label   "Conversational turn-kind scheme" ;
    rdfs:comment "Closed 5-concept scheme of conversational-turn classifications. Every individual below is an INPUT tag a turn is hand- or upstream-classified with; hook.ttl's CONSTRUCT query only ever READS these, never assigns them from turn text." .

smon:GroundingQuestion
    a             smon:TurnKind , skos:Concept ;
    skos:inScheme smon:TurnKindScheme ;
    skos:notation "grounding-question" ;
    skos:prefLabel "GroundingQuestion" ;
    rdfs:comment  "A turn asking a clarifying/scoping question about which system or capability is in play, before committing to an approach." .

smon:SurveyResponse
    a             smon:TurnKind , skos:Concept ;
    skos:inScheme smon:TurnKindScheme ;
    skos:notation "survey-response" ;
    skos:prefLabel "SurveyResponse" ;
    rdfs:comment  "A turn that only surveys/summarizes the current state (reads code, greps, reports findings) without running or building anything new." .

smon:RunResponse
    a             smon:TurnKind , skos:Concept ;
    skos:inScheme smon:TurnKindScheme ;
    skos:notation "run-response" ;
    skos:prefLabel "RunResponse" ;
    rdfs:comment  "A turn that actually runs/builds/executes something (a test, a command, a real artifact change) rather than merely surveying." .

smon:BlockerResponse
    a             smon:TurnKind , skos:Concept ;
    skos:inScheme smon:TurnKindScheme ;
    skos:notation "blocker-response" ;
    skos:prefLabel "BlockerResponse" ;
    rdfs:comment  "A turn reporting that further progress is blocked on something outside the responder's control (a missing credential, an external approval, a genuinely underdetermined product decision)." .

smon:Other
    a             smon:TurnKind , skos:Concept ;
    skos:inScheme smon:TurnKindScheme ;
    skos:notation "other" ;
    skos:prefLabel "Other" ;
    rdfs:comment  "Any turn not classified as one of the four kinds above." .

# ── L5-push additions: obligation parameters (severity, deadline hint) ────
# See the "L5-PUSH ADDITIONS" header block above for full disclosure of why
# each of these exists and what public terms were checked and rejected.

smon:Severity
    a            rdfs:Class ;
    rdfs:label   "Severity" ;
    rdfs:comment "Closed 3-concept severity scheme (Low/Medium/High) for a derived smon:EscalationObligation. Computed by smon:prioritize_escalation_obligation (hook.ttl) from a real COUNT aggregate over same-topic repeat GroundingQuestion turns -- never a hardcoded constant." .

smon:SeverityScheme
    a            skos:ConceptScheme ;
    rdfs:label   "Escalation severity scheme" .

smon:Low    a smon:Severity , skos:Concept ; skos:inScheme smon:SeverityScheme ; skos:notation "low"    ; skos:prefLabel "Low" ;    rdfs:comment "Exactly 2 same-topic GroundingQuestion turns total (the minimum that can fire the hook at all)." .
smon:Medium a smon:Severity , skos:Concept ; skos:inScheme smon:SeverityScheme ; skos:notation "medium" ; skos:prefLabel "Medium" ; rdfs:comment "3 same-topic GroundingQuestion turns total." .
smon:High   a smon:Severity , skos:Concept ; skos:inScheme smon:SeverityScheme ; skos:notation "high"   ; skos:prefLabel "High" ;   rdfs:comment "4 or more same-topic GroundingQuestion turns total -- the system has been asked about repeatedly and survey-only responses have not resolved it." .

smon:severity
    a            rdf:Property ;
    rdfs:label   "severity" ;
    rdfs:domain  smon:EscalationObligation ;
    rdfs:range   smon:Severity ;
    rdfs:comment "How urgent this escalation is, computed from the real count of same-topic GroundingQuestion turns in the session (see smon:Severity). A parameter a downstream planner can branch on, not a bare unparameterized obligation node." .

smon:DeadlineHint
    a            rdfs:Class ;
    rdfs:label   "DeadlineHint" ;
    rdfs:comment "Closed 2-concept categorical urgency-window scheme (ActNow/NextSession). Deliberately categorical, not xsd:dateTime: this engine does not implement arithmetic FILTER expressions (Expression::Add/Subtract; see smon:immediatelyFollows's disclosure above), so a fabricated absolute deadline the hook cannot actually compute is never asserted." .

smon:DeadlineHintScheme
    a            skos:ConceptScheme ;
    rdfs:label   "Escalation deadline-hint scheme" .

smon:ActNow      a smon:DeadlineHint , skos:Concept ; skos:inScheme smon:DeadlineHintScheme ; skos:notation "act-now"      ; skos:prefLabel "ActNow" ;      rdfs:comment "Bound to smon:High severity: the escalation should be actuated in the current session, not deferred." .
smon:NextSession a smon:DeadlineHint , skos:Concept ; skos:inScheme smon:DeadlineHintScheme ; skos:notation "next-session" ; skos:prefLabel "NextSession" ; rdfs:comment "Bound to smon:Low/smon:Medium severity: worth surfacing, not yet urgent enough to interrupt the current session." .

smon:deadlineHint
    a            rdf:Property ;
    rdfs:label   "deadlineHint" ;
    rdfs:domain  smon:EscalationObligation ;
    rdfs:range   smon:DeadlineHint ;
    rdfs:comment "Categorical urgency window, deterministically bound to smon:severity by smon:prioritize_escalation_obligation (hook.ttl): High -> ActNow, Low/Medium -> NextSession." .

# ── L5-push additions: obligation lifecycle (status, discharge, refusal) ──

smon:ObligationStatus
    a            rdfs:Class ;
    rdfs:label   "ObligationStatus" ;
    rdfs:comment "Closed 3-concept lifecycle-state scheme (Open/Discharged/Refused) for smon:EscalationObligation. Every obligation is born smon:Open (asserted by the derivation hook itself); a transition to Discharged or Refused is a SEPARATE, later fact assertion -- this pack's hooks never self-transition an obligation's status, mirroring the CLASSIFICATION-IS-INPUT discipline applied to lifecycle state instead of turn-kind." .

smon:ObligationStatusScheme
    a            skos:ConceptScheme ;
    rdfs:label   "Obligation lifecycle-status scheme" .

smon:Open        a smon:ObligationStatus , skos:Concept ; skos:inScheme smon:ObligationStatusScheme ; skos:notation "open"        ; skos:prefLabel "Open" ;        rdfs:comment "Derived, not yet discharged or refused. Asserted by the derivation hook at CONSTRUCT time -- an obligation is always born in this state." .
smon:Discharged  a smon:ObligationStatus , skos:Concept ; skos:inScheme smon:ObligationStatusScheme ; skos:notation "discharged"  ; skos:prefLabel "Discharged" ;  rdfs:comment "The escalation was actually acted on (a real build/run happened). Requires smon:dischargedAt (xsd:dateTime) -- enforced by shapes.ttl." .
smon:Refused     a smon:ObligationStatus , skos:Concept ; skos:inScheme smon:ObligationStatusScheme ; skos:notation "refused"     ; skos:prefLabel "Refused" ;     rdfs:comment "The escalation was reviewed and explicitly declined (e.g. a human judged the repeat question was NOT actually the same underlying ask). Requires smon:refusalReason (xsd:string) -- enforced by shapes.ttl." .

smon:status
    a            rdf:Property ;
    rdfs:label   "status" ;
    rdfs:domain  smon:EscalationObligation ;
    rdfs:range   smon:ObligationStatus ;
    rdfs:comment "Current lifecycle state. queries/open_obligations.rq (shipped this pass) is the real, checked-in query surface: SELECT obligations WHERE smon:status smon:Open." .

smon:dischargedAt
    a            rdf:Property ;
    rdfs:label   "dischargedAt" ;
    rdfs:domain  smon:EscalationObligation ;
    rdfs:range   xsd:dateTime ;
    rdfs:comment "When a smon:Discharged obligation was actually acted on. Required together with smon:status smon:Discharged; see shapes.ttl." .

smon:refusalReason
    a            rdf:Property ;
    rdfs:label   "refusalReason" ;
    rdfs:domain  smon:EscalationObligation ;
    rdfs:range   xsd:string ;
    rdfs:comment "Why a smon:Refused obligation was declined. Required together with smon:status smon:Refused; see shapes.ttl." .

# ── L5-push additions: ungoverned-transition catch-all detector ───────────

smon:UngovernedTransition
    a            rdfs:Class ;
    rdfs:label   "UngovernedTransition" ;
    rdfs:comment "Derived by the companion hook smon:flag_ungoverned_transition (hook.ttl): a GroundingQuestion turn whose immediately-following response is smon:Other -- neither the one pattern this pack governs (SurveyResponse -> possible escalation) nor a RunResponse/BlockerResponse (the two kinds already proven, by README's adversarial check 1, never to warrant escalation). Scoped honestly to the grounding-question/response process this pack models, not the whole of Claude Code's behavior -- see ontology.ttl's L5-push header for why this is a real, positive, currently-narrow catch-all rather than a claim of total process coverage." .

smon:hasUngovernedResponse
    a            rdf:Property ;
    rdfs:label   "hasUngovernedResponse" ;
    rdfs:domain  smon:UngovernedTransition ;
    rdfs:range   smon:Turn ;
    rdfs:comment "Links an UngovernedTransition to the smon:Other-classified response turn that triggered the flag." .

smon:hasUngovernedQuestion
    a            rdf:Property ;
    rdfs:label   "hasUngovernedQuestion" ;
    rdfs:domain  smon:UngovernedTransition ;
    rdfs:range   smon:Turn ;
    rdfs:comment "Links an UngovernedTransition to the GroundingQuestion turn whose response was not governed by any known pattern." .

# ── L5-push (round 3) addition: overdue-obligation escalation ─────────────
#
# Matrix 2's Obligation-lifecycle L4 bar, verbatim: "Overdue/undischarged
# obligations escalate via the same hook mechanism." This pack's L3 state
# (round 2) recorded smon:status and made open/discharged/refused queryable,
# but nothing re-escalated an obligation that stayed Open. hook.ttl's new
# smon:escalate_overdue_obligation hook closes this: it fires when a
# smon:PrioritizedEscalationObligation is still smon:status smon:Open with
# smon:deadlineHint smon:ActNow (i.e. the policy said "act now") AND the
# session has since moved on to a later turn without the obligation being
# discharged or refused -- the SAME derivation mechanism (kh:Hook +
# SPARQL-CONSTRUCT via praxis_graphlaw's TripleStore::load_hook_pack +
# .materialize()) every other hook in this file uses, not a new code path.

smon:OverdueEscalationObligation
    a            rdfs:Class ;
    rdfs:label   "OverdueEscalationObligation" ;
    rdfs:comment "Derived by the companion hook smon:escalate_overdue_obligation (hook.ttl): a smon:PrioritizedEscalationObligation that was smon:status smon:Open with smon:deadlineHint smon:ActNow (High severity's ActNow policy) at the time a LATER turn in the same session occurred -- i.e. the deadline was violated because nothing discharged or refused it before the session moved on. This is a second-order escalation OF an existing obligation, not a new independent finding; smon:escalates links back to the original node." .

smon:escalates
    a            rdf:Property ;
    rdfs:label   "escalates" ;
    rdfs:domain  smon:OverdueEscalationObligation ;
    rdfs:range   smon:PrioritizedEscalationObligation ;
    rdfs:comment "Links an OverdueEscalationObligation back to the original smon:PrioritizedEscalationObligation whose ActNow deadline it found violated. The original node's own smon:status stays smon:Open (this pack's engine is append-only via kh:effect \"emit-delta\" -- no hook ever retracts a prior CONSTRUCT; overdue-ness is a new, additional derived fact layered on top, not a rewrite of the original)." .

smon:PrioritizedEscalationObligation
    a            rdfs:Class ;
    rdfs:label   "PrioritizedEscalationObligation" ;
    rdfs:subClassOf smon:EscalationObligation ;
    rdfs:comment "Derived by hook.ttl's smon:prioritize_escalation_obligation_{low,medium,high} hooks (round 2) instead of the older unparameterized smon:derive_escalation_obligation, so severity/deadlineHint/status can be attached without double-CONSTRUCTing the base smon:EscalationObligation shape. Declared formally here (round 3) so shapes.ttl and smon:escalates above have a real rdfs:Class to range/domain against instead of an implicit, undeclared type only ever seen inside hook.ttl's CONSTRUCT text." .

# ── L5-push (round 3) addition: actuation-closure re-observe facts ────────
#
# Matrix 2's Actuation-closure L4 bar, verbatim: "Actuation outcomes flow
# back into the graph as new facts (closed loop)." `scripts/
# actuate_escalation.py` (round 2) already fires on derivation and writes a
# JSON receipt, but that receipt lived OUTSIDE the RDF graph -- an artifact
# on disk, not itself a fact a later `ggen graph validate`/hook run could
# see or query. `scripts/actuate_escalation.py --emit-receipt-graph` (round
# 3) additionally renders the SAME receipt as a `smon:ActuationReceipt`
# individual in a NEW Turtle file, and the script's own `--verify-round-trip`
# mode re-loads ontology.ttl + the original input + that new receipt file
# into a FRESH TripleStore-equivalent graph and confirms the receipt fact is
# there and queryable -- a real re-observe step, not narrated. Honestly
# scoped: this closes derive -> actuate -> receipt -> re-observe for the
# RECEIPT record itself (hook-firing outcome, hash, timestamp), not
# per-derived-individual linkage back to the specific blank-node obligation
# it actuated (Turtle blank-node identifiers are not stable/referenceable
# across separate files/parses -- see fixtures/pattern-fires-discharged.ttl's
# header for this same disclosed constraint) -- see README's "Actuation
# closure" verification section for the exact scope and remaining gap.

smon:ActuationReceipt
    a            rdfs:Class ;
    rdfs:label   "ActuationReceipt" ;
    rdfs:comment "A re-observable RDF fact recording one scripts/actuate_escalation.py run: which input was actuated, whether any hook fired, and a hash of the derived triples. Written to a NEW Turtle file by --emit-receipt-graph (never appended to hook.ttl/ontology.ttl themselves), then re-loaded by --verify-round-trip to prove it is a queryable graph fact, not merely a JSON artifact on disk." .

smon:receiptHash
    a            rdf:Property ;
    rdfs:label   "receiptHash" ;
    rdfs:domain  smon:ActuationReceipt ;
    rdfs:range   xsd:string ;
    rdfs:comment "SHA-256 hex digest of the actuation's derived triples (same value as the JSON receipt's derived_triples_sha256 field -- one shared computation, two representations)." .

smon:actuatedAt
    a            rdf:Property ;
    rdfs:label   "actuatedAt" ;
    rdfs:domain  smon:ActuationReceipt ;
    rdfs:range   xsd:dateTime ;
    rdfs:comment "Wall-clock UTC timestamp of the actuation run." .

smon:anyHookFired
    a            rdf:Property ;
    rdfs:label   "anyHookFired" ;
    rdfs:domain  smon:ActuationReceipt ;
    rdfs:range   xsd:boolean ;
    rdfs:comment "Whether at least one kh:Hook derived any triple during this actuation run." .

smon:actuatedInput
    a            rdf:Property ;
    rdfs:label   "actuatedInput" ;
    rdfs:domain  smon:ActuationReceipt ;
    rdfs:range   xsd:string ;
    rdfs:comment "The input Turtle file path this receipt actuated against (a literal path string, not an IRI -- the input file's own individuals are not re-asserted here, only referenced by name)." .
